{ There are two choices that you need to make if you want to be a successful 1.d4 player.   The biggest decision for you to make is which line to choose against the Grünfeld, Nimzo-Indian, Benoni and the King's-Indian defences, not to mention the Benko/Volga Gambit, Budapest, Tango etc.  Or maybe there is another option of getting lively positions allowing you to play aggressively for the full point?   That's what this repertoire is about. My name is Kamil Plichta, I am a FIDE Master from Poland and I invite you to study my repertoire. I've worked hard studying chess openings for more than four years and I have been a 1. d4 player myself for over 15 years.   The realisation I had after all that time is that players have better repertoires with Black than White.  The reason for this is that it's more likely to land in a difficult position playing Black, because White has the first move so he will guide us what type of game he wants. So everyone is prepared against 1. e4 or 1. d4, forcing us to break their well-built defences.  So I would suggest not being so cooperative and striking as soon as on move 2!  There are a few reasons why 2. Bg5, The Trompowsky, is no worse than 2. c4:  - Objectively there is no advantage for White in the Nimzo-Indian or Grünfeld. In my opinion, the same statement can be made with regard to the King's Indian. That means that 2. c4 doesn't guarantee that even if you play the best moves you will have any advantage whatsoever.  - 2. Bg5 is a pretty rare guest  (much more popular alternatives are the London)   2.Bf4   or  2.Nf3  lines in over the board play. This means your opponents will less often be prepared to face such an aggressive move as  2.Bg5   - Throughout the whole repertoire I worked with Stockfish. All lines that I offer are backed up by analysis with the strongest engine.  - You avoid tons of theory and save yourself a huge amount of time to spend on different chess-related stuff and areas of study, which is a big bonus!  Don't get me wrong: objectively speaking there is no advantage in The Trompowsky! However, what I can guarantee you is that you will get many positions with attacking chances, where the only side who will have a lot of fun is White.  I would never state that The Trompowsky is a move that forces Black to abandon  1...Nf6.  It's simply not true. With correct play Black will be able to reach positions which are close to being equal, but definitely no more than that.  And the path to a playable position is pretty narrow for our opponent. If you don't want to study novelties on move 20-25 trying to remember all the theory of the main lines  (not to mention hundreds of hours to do that)  (, then we probably speak the same language.  The same thinking process came to one of the greatest chess minds. My compatriot and one of the best polish players in history - Jan-Krzysztof Duda played The Trompowsky in every possible game during the World Blitz Championship 2018 and he took 2nd place)  (only half a point behind Carlsen and 2 points ahead of Nakamura!)  (. He has scored many crushing victories with The Trompowsky, even against 2700+ players    So, I wish you all as much fun learning my Trompowsky repertoire as I had making it.  Welcome to the Trompowsky World! You will not regret it.  FM Kamil Plichta, Koszalin 2019) }
