{ My friendship with Kamil Plichta began many years ago. We had a lot of mutual friends and we spent a lot of time together at parties or playing soccer.  Back then I knew that he was a chess player on around the 2200 level.  But there was something intriguing about him, he was extremely passionate about chess. I noticed that he had a lot of chess books mainly focused on the theory. It was quite surprising for me that he was so passionate about chess.  When I had to face him over the board it was always a little bit unpleasant for me because I knew that he had an extensive base of theoretical knowledge and I had problems avoiding his preparation.  Fortunately, only a couple of our games are listed in the databases and the overall score is 2-1 for me. However, in reality there were many more games and some of them finished with very quick knockouts right out of the opening.  A few years ago Kamil started creating opening files. He sent a lot of those files to me and I started using them. If I had to use one word to describe them it would be definitely... sharp. A lot of those lines create problems for the opponent at the very beginning.  Of course, we have to remember that if your opponent is well prepared we are not going to get much in openings like the Trompowsky. But developments in theory have shown that even in main lines objectively Black is able to equalize.  The Trompowsky can be used as a very dangerous weapon to surprise the opponent. The lines given in this course are mostly very clear with simple instructions on what we have to do.  I would like to recommend this repertoire to all the players willing to extend their opening knowledge. I am sure many readers will benefit significantly as I did.     GM Kamil Dragun, Brownsville, TX 2019 }
