1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5
{ This move was popularized by the Brazilian chess player Octavio Trompowsky. White doesn't play  2.c4  , but has other aggressive intentions. Instead of occupying the centre with pawns, we want to develop as fast as possible and start attacking Black's position. This weapon was championed by such players as Hodgson, Wells or Miladinovic. }
2... Ne4
{ We should consider this as a main move, because it is played most often. By playing 2... Ne4, Black avoids his pawns being doubled after the immediate 3. Bxf6 and asks us 'What are we going to do with the attacked Bishop ?' }
3. h4
{ And now the fun begins. This variation has the coolest name in chess - THE RAPTOR! After only three moves we have a very strange position. Both sides broke the basic chess rules - Black moved his Knight twice  (and he will move it a 3rd time for sure)  and White developed the Bishop before the Knights and also played a flank move with his h-pawn. However, this situation can be hugely advantageous for us, because many players on the Black side won't be familiar with many subtleties. You would think that by playing like this your opponent could use an engine to prepare against you and surely punish you for breaking the basic strategic rules. This is simply not the case. I checked all of my analysis with the modern engines, and none of them give an advantage for Black. You can be sure, that this is not a typical 'Play X and win' book with a lot of holes in the analysis. }
3... c5 { A critical try. The alternatives will be analysed later. } 4. d5
{ Of course we don't miss a chance to seize some space and offer a pawn or two for an attack.  4.dxc5  would be a very anti-positional continuation which we won't look at. }
4... Qb6 5. Nd2
{ The real gambit. Now Black is obliged to accept our pawn offer to prove that his previous play had any sense. }
5... Nxd2 6. Bxd2 Qxb2 { Otherwise White will play Bc3 and have an advantage. }
7. Nf3
{ This is the correct move order. Note that after the immediate  7.e4  Black can play  7...Qe5.  Here we eliminate that possibility, because now the e5-square is protected by the Knight. }
7... d6 8. e4
{ Black already has problems completing his development. White on the other hand will continue with moves like h4 - h5, Rb1 and a well-timed e4 - e5. }
