{ An amazing concept. At first it looks dubious, because it opens the g7-Bishop and closes the centre. On the other hand Blacks light-squared Bishop is buried alive. Although objectively this position is equal, I would prefer to play it with White in a practical game, as Black needs to be precise not to lose at once. Our next moves will be c2 - c4 / Rb3 and possibly Kf1, while after ...g5 - g4 we go Rh4. }
15... g4 { 15...Na6  then  16.c4 } 16. Rh4 Bf6 17. g3
{ Note that  17.Rxg4  is less accurate, because Black can reply with  17...Qf5  and we can't protect our Bishop. }
17... Qh6 18. Bxg4 Bxh4 19. Nxh4
{ White has excellent compensation, as all of Black's pieces are not active and his queenside has no prospects. }
