{ I will just briefly mention the interesting alternatives to move 3. d5.3. Bxf6 is also a strong move and it was analysed by GM Kryakvin. If you want to look for an alternative to 3. d5 to broaden your repertoire, then 3. Bxf6 would be my suggestion. I also have huge experience in the 3. Nc3 line. However, that move leads nowhere after Black's strongest response 3... d5 as proposed by GM Boris Avrukh. }
3... Qb6
{ The most topical continuation. Black attacks the b2-pawn and we are obliged to sacrifice it  (If you thought about Bc1 for a second - shame on you !) }
4. Nc3 { This is called the Vaganian Gambit. } 4... Qxb2 5. Bd2 Qb6
{ Rb1 followed by Nb5 was threatened so this is the only move. Black wasted 3 moves with his Queen to grab the b2-pawn. We have a very simple plan - push the central pawns as far as possible. We will probably win another tempo on Blacks Queen. Also our lead in development and space advantage will give us a long lasting initiative for a mere pawn. }
6. e4
{ Now Black has two choices - he will either go 6... d6 or 6... e5. The current theory gives 6... d6 as dangerous for Black, while 6... e5 is known to be quite solid. I disagree. Black will have big problems after either move. }
6... e5 7. g4 h6 { This is the only sensible move stopping g5. } 8. f4
{ We are going to play f5 next. } 8... d6
{ The only move.   8...exf4?  9.e5  Ng8  10.d6  and Black can safely resign. }
9. f5 Be7
{ This is Black's most popular move. We have reached the position that usually appears via the 7. f4 d6 8. f5 h6 9. g4 Be7 move order. }
10. h4
{ Simple and strong. White needs to prepare g5, and our usual way of doing this is by playing Qf3 to defend the h1-Rook. }
10... Qd8
{ 10...h5  11.Rb1  leads to the game Prie - Tripoteau   10...Na6  11.Rb1  followed by Qf3 and g5.   10...a6  10.a4  Qd8  11.Qf3  in both cases with a great position for White. }
11. Qf3 Nh7
{ Played in all games that reached this position.   11...Nfd7  is interesting but has never been played. I think that it is fair to keep this line as the clickable variation. I suggest playing  12.g5!  hxg5  13.hxg5  Rxh1  14.Qxh1  Bxg5  15.Qh8+  Nf8  16.Qxg7  with a big advantage for White. }
12. Qg3
{ Sooner or later, White will crash through the kingside. We already threaten g5. }
12... Rg8
{ Stepping out of the h-file and discouraging g5.   12...Nf8  13.Nf3  is similar. }
13. Nf3 f6 { This move makes sure that Black won't be able to move anything. }
14. Be2
{ White should now abandon plans connected with g5, because it would exchange too much material. We can play Nh2 - f1 - e3 - c4 followed by a4, Rb1 and if Black doesn't play ... a6 - Nb5. Then everything will be ready for g5. If Black plays ... a6, we will push the a-pawn to a5 and put pressure on the b-file. In my opinion, White is winning. }
