{ This is the 2nd most popular move after 2... Ne4. Black wants to play 3... h6 forcing us to take on f6 - since the e4-pawn will not be defended after we play 3. e4 - Black will recapture on f6 with the Queen gaining the bishop pair without having a crippled pawn structure. On the other hand , we gain a lead in development which we should make use of as fast as possible. }
3. e4
{ White has some decent alternatives, but this move is in the spirit of the Trompowsky. We get a big centre and will try to squeeze Black. White can try two moves here: First one is 3. Nd2 which leads to more calm and steady positions. White will not be forced to take on f6 with his Bishop and can develop smoothly. Usually we want to go for e2 - e4 if Black gives us a chance. It would be interesting to have this move as a backup line. The second option here is to go 3. Nf3 which transposes to the Torre Attack. }
3... h6 4. Bxf6
{ After any other move we would lose the e4-pawn, but no worries - we will gain a huge lead in the development by giving up the Bishop pair. }
4... Qxf6 5. c3
{ I like this modern move the most. We solidify the centre preparing to develop our Bishop to c4, Knight to e2 and then castle kingside with f2 - f4 to come. }
5... d5
{ This alternative to 5... d6 is quite popular. Black strikes at the White's centre and forces us to play precisely to get anything. }
6. Bd3 { This is stronger than 6. Nd2 which gives Black equality. } 6... dxe4
{ This is too cooperative. Voluntarily giving up the centre rarely serves a good purpose. }
7. Bxe4 c5 8. Nf3 cxd4 9. O-O
{ In my opinion, this is a better move than 9. Nxd4, which I picked as our mainline over a year ago. The old 9. Nxd4 line can be found here.   The problem with the move  9.Nxd4  is  9...Bc5!  and Black has a comfortable position, and enjoys the pair of Bishops.  By playing 9. O-O, White sacrifices the pawn for the initiative. }
9... dxc3
{ After  9...Bd6  we can choose  10.Qxd4   10.cxd4  O-O  11.Nc3  with nicely centralized pieces is also possible.  10...Qxd4  11.Nxd4  Nd7  12.Nd2  White plans to play Nc4.  Black's best move is  12...Nb6  but after  13.a4  a5  14.Nb5  White still has the initiative. }
10. Nxc3 Be7 { Black is one move from castling. } 11. Qa4+
{ It is essential to spoil Black's plans of safeguarding the King. } 11... Bd7
12. Qb3 Nc6 13. Qxb7 Rb8 14. Qa6 Rb6 15. Qe2 O-O 16. Rfd1
{ White got the pawn back, and will play Rac1 next with nicely centralized pieces. The position is around equal. }
