1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 d5
{ This is the 3rd most popular move, but I consider it to be the most problematic for us. What do I mean by 'problematic'? It means that if we want to continue in the Trompowsky spirit, then we have to take on f6 at some point and after Black recaptures with ...gxf6 he will have a fair share of chances. The database games I found confirm this, with around 50% winning for either White and Black. On the other hand we will get positions that we should understand better than our opponent. The reason for this is simple - the position after Bxf6 will appear once every 150-200 games for our opponent, while for us it will be like once every 10-15 games. This should give us a nice practical advantage over our rivals. Also for a lot of people playing with a crippled structure from move 3 on is not ideal. }
3. Bxf6
{ 3. e3 sometimes transposes to the main lines, but I prefer the text move to limit Black's options. 3. Nf3 transposes to the Torre Attack and 3. Nc3 leads to the Veresov Opening. If you - dear reader - feel comfortable playing any of these openings, then it is always good to have those as backup lines. However, if we want to stay in Trompowsky territory, then taking on f6 is obligatory. }
3... gxf6
{ One of the basic chess rules tells us to capture towards the centre to increase our control over it. }
4. e3
{ This should give us more options of fighting for an advantage than 4. c4, which leads to quite dull and equal positions with one exception. There is one specific line after 4. c4 that is very interesting and I will give it to you as a secondary option. }
4... Bf5 5. c4 { Here it is logical to attack enemy's centre immediately. }
5... c6 6. Qb3 Qc7
{ Black avoids the Queens exchange which would happen after ... Qb6. } 7. cxd5
cxd5 { Black keeps the pawn on d5 alive due to the ... Qc1 counterattack. } 8.
Bb5+ Bd7 { 8...Nc6?  would enable  9.Qxd5. } 9. Nc3 e6 10. Rc1
{ We will continue developing with Nf3 or even Nge2. White has a good version of the Exchange Slav, with the pawns doubled on f6. }
