{ As I said we can't castle too early, because of the possible march of the h-pawn when Black's attack becomes dangerous. His King is very safe in the centre while ours would be a target.  8.O-O ?!  would be an inaccuracy  8...Nf6  9.b3  trying to play as in  6..O-O  line is very suspicious here. After  9...h5  I already dislike this position. Black has a clear plan of throwing the kitchen sink at our King. Also continuing with  8.b3  is risky, because of  8...Nf6  9.c4  Bb4+  and we have no good way to react to that check. After  10.Nd2  there comes ...  Ne4  with an advantage for Black.  8.b3  Nf6  9.c4  Bb4+  10.Kf1  misplaces our King, but it was a move that Victor Laznicka played against David Howell in 2008. Finally  8.b3  Nf6  9.c4  Bb4+  10.Nbc3  leads to a draw by perpetual after  Qa5  11.Qd3  Ne4  12.Rc1  Ba3  and  ...Bb4-Ba3. }
8... Nf6 9. c4
{ Now we can see the difference - our knight is on d2 instead of c3 where it is less active.   9.O-O  h5  is still a problem. }
9... dxc4 10. Nxc4 Bc7 11. O-O O-O 12. b4
{ I think that gaining space on the queenside and going for the quick b4 - b5 is the most consistent plan. Black will look for his chances on the kingside, but our attack on the queenside should be faster. Typical moves that we want to play are a2 - a4 followed by b4 - b5 and then our g2-Bishop will show its full power. }
