{ I want to share a word or two about the alternative move order. White is not forced to play 3. Bxf6, although it should be our main option. However, if you like to keep your game as flexible as possible, here are some points of the 3. e3 move order. Firstly, PROS:  1. We avoid the 3... exf6 line. The reason for that is that 3. Bxf6 exf6 is a perfectly playable option - and for some people might be annoying.   If we start with  3.e3  and our opponent replies with  3...c5  , then we play  4.Bxf6  and here,  4...gxf6  is the best move for Black.  The reason for that can be seen in this line. Taking with the e-pawn combines pretty badly with ... d5, because the d5-pawn is left isolated.  2. We might provoke our opponent to play something passive like 3... Nbd7, and we will get a great Torre-like position after 4. Bd3.  Now CONS:  1. First, and the most important one is that after 3. e3 Black might play 3... Ne4 and after 4. h4 we are tricked from our Raptor move order - we play 2... Ne4 3. h4 d5 4. Nd2 - here, instead of Nd2 we have e3 played. However, things are still quite bright for us, because after 3. e3 Ne4, we might play 4. Bf4 and we avoided the ... c5 lines - the position after 4. Bf4 is considered to be good for White.  2. If Black avoids 3... c5, he might play 3... e6 and we are kicked from our repertoire vs 2... e6.  The choice is yours! I use both of these lines depending on my mood and I very often adjust to a certain opponent. }
